# Changelog policy

Every commit made under `60-git-commit.mdc` that changes user-facing or
developer-facing behavior gets a matching `CHANGELOG.md` entry, added in the **same
commit** — never as a separate follow-up commit.

- Use Keep-a-Changelog style structure: a dated heading per work session or logical
  release chunk, with `### Added`, `### Changed`, `### Fixed`, `### Removed`
  sub-sections as applicable.
- Each entry is one line, written for a future reader who wasn't in this session:
  explain *why* when the reason isn't obvious from the description alone. Example:
  `- Removed edit/history tab markup — no server backend to act on it, see
  docs/RESEARCH.md.` rather than just `- Removed edit/history tab markup.`
- Skip an entry only for genuinely non-user-facing internal churn (comment fixes, minor
  formatting) — use judgment; the goal is a changelog someone can read end-to-end to
  understand the project's evolution, not a mechanical mirror of every commit hash.
- If a change reverses or significantly modifies an earlier changelog entry from the
  same unreleased section, edit that entry in place rather than adding a contradictory
  new one — keep the changelog internally consistent, not just append-only.
